AU  - Salam, M. A.
AU  - Siddique, A. B.
AU  - Subrata Banik, Subrata Banik
AU  - Rahman, K.
TI  - Hybrid rice technology and its sustainability at the farm level: a study on food security for farm households.
T2  - International Journal of Sustainable Agricultural Technology
M3  - Journal article
AB  - The present study was undertaken in order to examine adoption rate of hybrid rice at the farm level, area shifting to hybrid rice from HYVs, comparative profitability of hybrid rice to HYVs, document consumer's preferences and constraints towards adoption of hybrid rice. Data were collected by conducting farm level survey in favorable; flood prone, drought prone, saline and Tidal Submergence areas of Bangladesh during Boro season, 2009-2010. First one district from each of the environment was selected. Then one upazila from each of the district and finally one village under each of the upazila were chosen. Twenty farmers were chosen from each of the village randomly for sample and thus, total sample size was 100. The findings of the study revealed that the study area under hybrid rice has been in declining trend in all production environments over the period, 2007-2010, although, it has been quite a bit increasing trend in flood prone areas over the same period. Trend area of BRRIdhan 28 has been at per in all production environments over the period of 2007-2010, although it has been a bit decreasing trend in flood prone areas. Although, the yield performance of hybrid rice (5 to 7 t/ha) fluctuated substantially in all production environments over the period, 2007-2010, but it was quite impressive than BRRI dhan 28. Unit cost of hybrid rice production was a bit lower compared to HYVs in all production environments, since its grain yield was higher (42% in favorable, 74% in flood prone areas, 14% in drought prone areas, 13% in salinity and 23% in tidal submergence areas) compared to HYVs. BCR for hybrid rice under all production situation was quite a bit higher, except saline areas due to higher irrigation cost which was paid by the arrangement of crop sharing (one forth of total output). Sixty nine percent hybrid rice growers showed their enthusiasm to continue growing hybrid rice expecting better yield in the next season; while thirty one percent was not interested to continue due to higher costs of seed, pest/disease infestation and less market demand. Majority of the farmers mentioned that availability of rice to farm families increased more than additional 30 days when they did not cultivate hybrid rice. Almost all farmers reported that frequent power disruption (Electricity) and lack of knowledge about hybrid rice cultivation were major constraints to the expansion of this variety.
