AU  - [Anonymous]
TI  - Developing Kenya's drylands.
T2  - African Farming and Food Processing
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This article discusses how pastoralists' knowledge, resources, and networks can contribute to effective humanitarian response and resilience to shocks and uncertainties in Kenya's drylands. Researchers from the Centre for Research and Development in Drylands, the Feinstein International Centre, Tufts University, and the Institute of Development Studies Sussex conducted conversations with villagers in Moyale, Kenya, focusing on the 2020-2023 drought. Participants highlighted how the drought led to significant losses, forcing many to rely on producing charcoal fromProsopis juliflora. While this provided income, it was precarious, burdensome, and illegal. The introduction ofProsopis juliflorain the 1970s, ostensibly to rehabilitate degraded rangelands, has had negative impacts on pastoralists, particularly affecting their pay-outs from livestock insurance programmes. The study also highlights how well-meaning development interventions, such as the construction of a large building in Isiolo, often fail to serve intended goals and can exacerbate vulnerability. The research underscores the importance of integrating pastoralists' knowledge, assets, and networks into development, resilience, humanitarian, and early warning interventions to ensure they articulate with, rather than undermine, pastoral livelihoods.
