TI  - Animal Comfort System Integration Crop-Livestock-Forest .
T2  - Informe Agropecuario
M3  - Journal article
AB  - According to forecast, the tropical and subtropical regions will be mostly affected by climate changes. However, regardless of this scenario, hot and humid environments, are often found in different regions of Brazil, making protocols can be extremely uncomfortable for dairy cows, subjecting them to a process known as heat stress. Management strategies can mitigate the effects of heat stress, by the provision of shade in order to reduce the incident radiation. In this context, a new system of which is called Integrated Crop-Livestock-Forestry (ICLF), which refers to the cultivation of trees associated with and /or shrubs, herbaceous plants (agricultural crops and /or pasture) and /or animals in the same unit management and in accordance with a spatial arrangement, temporal or both. Experiments conducted by researchers from the Embrapa Dairy Cattle in assessing the behaviour and performance of female dairy grazing systems, access to shade or not natural (composed of different tree species), showed that shading reduced the pasture Radiant Thermal Load (RTL), the index of black globe temperature and humidity (BGT) and the temperature under the canopy of trees. Afforestation of pastures contributed to increase grazing time and ruminating and idle time was reduced. The data obtained from these studies indicate an increase in performance translates to greater weight gain and milk production of animals in pasture shaded. It was noted, also, that there was a positive effect of afforestation on pastures by reducing the temperature of the body surface, respiratory rate and sweating rate (SR), which reflects better the thermal comfort of animals.
