TI  - Socio-economic importance of camel among the Pokot and Turkana communities of North Rift Valley Kenya.
T2  - Proceedings of the International Camel Conference, Al-Hasa, Saudi Arabia, 17-20 February 2013
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - The pokot are an indigenous, cattle-loving people who live in North Western Kenya and the Uganda border region some are primary farmers and other only keep cattle, sheep, goats and camels butPokotdo both as they move from one environment to another. Like other East African pastoralist their lives depend on the rain which is often scarce averaging 10 to 15 inches a year one the plain. Traditionally herders live mostly on milk, blood and occasionally meat of their animals and farmers grow millets, sorghum and corn to supplement the milk from their animals. Living traditionalpokotlife means tending to the herd or farm chores performing rituals of passage or protection. One is expected to be generous and friendly and to honour the traditional laid down by the ancestors and by God (Tororot) every young children help with milking herding and household cores rites of passage to adulthood include (sapana) for boys, circumcision for both boys and girls, pregnancy, marriage, child birth initiation, death, sickness natural disasters, murder and many other events are recognized through prescribed ritual. Sustainable livelihood approaches have evolved over many years from past experiences in development they are based on the best practices and in various forms.
