AU  - Pancharoen, Jiraporn
TI  - Raising southern indigenous cattle in Patthalung Province.
T2  - Kaen Kaset = Khon Kaen Agriculture Journal
M3  - Journal article
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - This study needs to know the basic information about raising cattle in Patthalung province. This study used Snowball sampling methods. Farmers were interviewed by questionnaire from September 2014 to February 2015. Data from 39 farmers in 10 districts were male 76.9 percent female 23.1 percent. The farmer raised cattle part-time. They had 11-20 years of experience and had farming areas of less than 10 hectares. The landowners were 97 percent. They had income of 10,001-50,000 baht per year from cattle and outcome from cattle less than 10,000 baht per year. They raised cattle free grazing in their area for a day and brought them back to the farm at night (81.6 percent). The most forage were Napier grass and para grass (94.7 percent), supplemented with straw (51.4 percent). Most farmers had their cattle dewormed (81.6 percent) and farmer did not vaccinate their cattle (52.6 percent). Farmers sold cattle to retailers or farmers in Patthalung. Most cattle were sold to farmers who wanted fighting bull (56.4 percent). Most farmers estimated cattle weight by sight (83.3 percent). Farmers needed help from the government to feed cattle in the dry season and flooding. A study of the system of production, problems in the management areas, and body condition of southern indigenous cattle in Patthalung province will be made aware of the readiness to develop cattle. When it is developed, it will make a sustainable farm.
