TI  - Demographic determinants of size of dairy herd: evidence from Punjab, India.
T2  - Agricultural Research Journal
M3  - Journal article
AB  - India after the operation flood in 1960s has emerged, from the shortage of milk at the time of independence, as a top-ranking milk producing country in the world. India's contribution to world milk production rose from 5% in 1970 to 20% in 2018. Now, the country is largely self -sufficient in milk production. The unique aspect of India's dairy sector is the predominance of small producers. Average dairy herd size in the country is just two. In comparison, countries such as US and Oceania have dairy herd size of 191 and 355, respectively (Ramakumar, 2019). India's dairy sector provides livelihood to about 70 million households. India is witnessing tremendous growth in the dairy sector due to rise in market demand, expanding urban population, changing lifestyles, and increasing health consciousness (Kumar et al, 2014). In rural India, dairy farming is at forefront in generating additional employment, income, empowerment of women, and as an important mechanism for coping with family emergencies (Thirunavukkarasu, 2016). Also due to formalization of Indian dairy sector, food safety regulations are becoming increasingly important in the dairy sector in India. The country has more than 355 million cows and buffalo for dairy production. The number of milch animals has seen a steady rise in the country. Punjab, though being amongst the largest milk producers has seen a steady decline in milch animal population. Contribution of Punjab in country's total milk production has also shown a decline from 9.5% to 6.8% in last 20 years. In this context, it is important to understand the factors that encourage farmers to have a larger dairy herd. Thus, this study attempts to understand how the demographic factors influence the households' choice of engaging with milch animals.
