TI  - Strategies for increasing fodder production in dryland agriculture.
T2  - Indian Dairyman
M3  - Journal article
AB  - The Working Group on Animal Husbandry and Dairying of the Planning Commission in India has estimated that by 2025, the demand and supply gap (deficit) would be 65% for green fodder and 25% for dry fodder. Nearly 60% of the cattle population inhabits rainfed areas, and the shortage of fodder is the main constraint for livestock production. The reasons vary from frequent droughts, shrinkage of common grazing lands, increased livestock populations and the introduction of crossbred cattle. To overcome these constraints, measures like inclusion of fodder crops in National Watershed Development Programmes for Rainfed Areas (NWDPRA), planting of fodder trees and growing fodder grasses on wastelands, developing non-conventional crop byproducts like sunhemp heads, castor cake, etc. as livestock feed and promotion of fodder crops as crops in the rabi season in well-irrigated lands are suggested. Besides extension strategies like the promotion of silvipastoral and agroforestry systems in farmer fields, creating awareness, laying of frontline demonstrations, supply of seeds/seedlings, growing fodder crops in common property resources like tank beds, establishment of nurseries and fodder demonstration farms by AH state departments and dairy milk unions and social fencing are suggested to popularize and increase fodder cultivation and availability.
