TI  - Socio-economic analysis of smallholder coffee farms with reference to integrated management of white stem borer in Karnataka, India.
T2  - ASIC 2004. 20th International Conference on Coffee Science, Bangalore, India, 11-15 October 2004
M3  - Book chapter
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - Coffee white stem borer (Xylotrechus quadripes) is the most destructive pest of arabica coffee in India, causing severe economic losses. In this context, a socioeconomic survey of 340 growers, randomly selected over three principal arabica coffee growing districts in Karnataka, was carried out during the 2003-04 cropping season. The study investigated farmers' perceptions of the importance of stem borer management and the farm practices influencing the pest. All the growers rated white stem borer as the major constraint in arabica cultivation. Unable to bear the economic burden, several small plantations have been left neglected, without use of any inputs like fertilizers and plant protection measures. Lack of proper shade because of the extraction of timber, prolonged drought, and poor management have increased the borer problem in the holdings. Many farmers expressed that BHC was more effective than other plant protection chemicals against the stem borer. The major constraints faced by the growers in arabica coffee cultivation are: severe incidence of white stem borer causing reduced yields (93.57%); low prices (90.71%); higher labour wages and lower level of work efficiency (45.71%); lack of skilled labour (12.14%); high cost of fertilizers and plant protection chemicals (74.29%); failure of rainfall (87.14%); and high rate of interest on borrowings (42.86%). Growers adopt mainly mechanical control measures like tracing and uprooting, as well as swabbing with lindane during April-May and September-December. The growers want newer technologies like acoustic detectors/sensors for the exact identification of borer-infested plants and also for the better management of the pest.
