TI  - Silvopastoral systems enhance the resilience of warm-season grasses by increasing minimum temperatures across seasons.
T2  - Agriculture, Ecosystems & Environment
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Sustainable intensification of agricultural systems requires strategies to strengthen the ecological resilience of pastures in the face of climate variability. In subtropical regions where warm and cool-season grasses coexist seasonally, the functional roles of tree inclusion and crop-grassland rotation in shaping grassland dynamics remain poorly understood. Based on a long-term field experiment in its eighth year, we evaluated, over two consecutive years, the effects of two approaches - tree inclusion as a nature-based solution and crop rotation as a temporal diversification strategy - on the composition and seasonal behavior of forage species. The study included four production systems: sole-livestock, livestock-forestry, crop-livestock, and crop-livestock-forestry. Previous maize crop cultivation in the crop-livestock and crop-livestock-forestry systems had minimal impact on altering the seasonal behavior of forage species. Conversely, tree presence led to significantly higher minimum temperatures during colder months, with an average increase of 3°C. This reduced frost intensity, accelerated the regrowth of warm-season grasses, and supported their dominance during the growing season, with these species accounting for over 85% of the biomass in tree-based systems. Although tree inclusion reduced the biomass of cool-season grasses, this microclimatic buffering contributed to greater pasture stability and functionality throughout the year. Our results show that silvopastoral systems can be a strategic approach for mitigating adverse climatic effects and strengthening the resilience of productive landscapes in subtropical zones. In these systems, tree presence may reduce species diversity but promotes functional specialization and greater temporal stability, ultimately contributing to year-round forage persistence. Trees thus act not only as structural components of production systems but also as ecological regulators, shaping plant community dynamics and stabilizing ecosystem function.
