AU  - Salam, Md Abdus
AU  - Anik, Asif Reza
AU  - Khan, Md. Akhtaruzzaman
AU  - Sharna, Shaima Chowdhury
TI  - Production risk and efficiency of fish farms in Bangladesh: a panel data analysis.
T2  - Aquaculture Economics & Management
M3  - Journal article
AB  - The study examines the production risk (PR) and technical efficiency (TE) of Bangladeshi fish farms using stochastic frontier analysis, using 1,056 observations from 352 fish farms over three years. Findings show that pond size and fingerlings have risk-increasing effects, while labor, other inputs, and cultivation of rohu (Labeo rohita) and shrimp are risk-reducing, suggesting that risk-averse farmers are more likely to use smaller ponds, fewer fingerlings, and more labor and other inputs and along with rohu and shrimp than risk-neutral farmers. The estimated TE is 0.743, suggesting 25.7% potential production losses due to inefficiency and PR. Fish farms experienced 6.9% and 3.8% lower efficiency in 2011 and 2018, respectively, compared to 2015. Year-specific SFA results reveal that the fish farm experienced a 6.9% lower frontier production and a 3.8% lower efficiency in 2018 compared to 2015, indicating a 10.7% decline in productivity from 2015 to 2018. Harvest frequency and mobile contact significantly increased TE, while education, salinity, and drought risk areas decreased TE. Decomposition analysis highlights labor, fish feed, and other variable inputs were major drivers of higher production in 2015. Policymakers could promote optimal stocking densities and scientific management practices through quality extension services to enhance sustainable fish production.
