AU  - Mclymont-Lafayette, I.
TI  - Local voices, global choices the Mocho oral testimony project, Jamaica.
T2  - International NGO Journal
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This article examines the Mocho community's experience of and responses to environmental and climate change issues under the Panos Oral Testimony Project spearheaded by the Panos Caribbean, a regional nongovernmental organization. The oral testimony of 47 men and women living in Mocho was taken and said testimony was completed and transcribed by April 2006. The community has experienced several extreme weather disturbances particularly Hurricane Ivan, most recently, and less dramatic but equally significant changes in the climate and the weather. When people describe the changes in their environment, the three issues of mining, hurricanes, and changes in weather patterns are interrelated. The testimonies contain accounts of how people would better prepare for hurricanes in the future, and also how farming has altered as a result of the changes in land use brought about by the mining industry. In September 2006, 65 men and women from Mocho discussed the issues emerging from the testimonies and the appropriate next steps for the community to take. As a result, four activities and additional training were scheduled from October 2006 to February 2007. In conclusion, the testimony collection has documented a wealth of knowledge and experiences on environmental change that would otherwise have been unrecorded, and has initiated wider interest, enthusiasm and activism amongst the community in addressing the environmental challenges they face.
