TI  - Effect of agroforestry systems on erodibility and hydraulic properties of Alfisols in eastern Himalayan region.
T2  - Indian Journal of Soil Conservation
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This study was carried out on five agroforestry systems (AFS) developed during 1987-1988 in Umiam, Meghalaya, India, to investigate the effect of AFS on erodibility and hydraulic conductivity of soils in the region. The AFS were: arboretum (mixed multipurpose tree species)+annual agricultural crops; Khasi mandarin (Citrus reticulata)+agricultural crops; Assam lemon (Citrus limon)+agricultural crops; silvi-horti-pastoral (Alnus nepalensis+pineapple+fodder grasses); and multi-storied AFS (Alnus nepalensis+tea+black pepper+agricultural crops). The species present in each AFS are given. Soil samples were collected from three sites of each agroforestry systems and were analysed for their mechanical composition and organic carbon. Soil erodibility factor, soil water retention and saturated hydraulic conductivity were determined. Soils under various AFS were mostly clay to silty clay in texture and acidic in nature. Moisture distribution pattern in the soil profile under various AFS during dry spell period of December-January revealed that the moisture content increased with increasing soil depth. Moisture equivalent under arboretum (39.78%) and silvi-horti-pastoral (39.67%) systems were almost at par and the corresponding values were higher than natural forest (37.20%). Irrespective of soil characteristics, the rate of unsaturated hydraulic conductivity and water diffusivity, invariably decreased with decrease in their water content. Significant improvement was observed in soil structure, pore size distribution and soil erodibility status under multistoried AFS and silvi-horti-pastoral systems for soil and water conservation in hilly ecosystem of northern states.
