TI  - National Conference on Pulses (NC Pulses 2026), Kanpur, India, 10-12 February 2026.
T2  - Journal of Food Legumes
M3  - Journal issue
M3  - Conference proceedings
AB  - This issue contains 20 articles providing information on the association of physiological traits with yield and related traits under drought conditions in lentil. One paper discusses the efficacy of imidazolinone herbicides on weed dynamics, productivity, and profitability of pigeon pea. Another article explores the introgression of bruchid resistance from Vigna radiatavar. sublobatainto green gram, evaluating resistance and yield potential. The identification of elite donors through agro-morphological characterization and anthracnose resistance screening of common bean accessions is also covered. A review paper examines the innovation continuum from trait discovery to deployment for efficient breeding of pulses. Other studies address India's journey towards pulse self-reliance, moth bean as a neglected legume with global promise, integrated weed management strategies for climate-resilient pulse production, and smart water management aiding efficient resource use in pulses. Some papers also discuss pulses for sustainable agriculture, organic farming involving pulse crops, mechanization challenges in pulse crops, effects of sowing window and row spacing on pigeon pea growth and yield, Trichodermaspp. as a sustainable pulse production tool, biotic stress dynamics in legumes under changing climates, adaptation strategies of major pulse crops under diverse climatic conditions, arid pulses for climate-resilient agriculture, socio-economic constraints to legume adoption among smallholders, and research gaps impeding genetic gain in pulses.
