TY  - BOOK
AU  - Chevalier, J. M.
AU  - Buckles, D. J.
ED  - Chevalier, J. M.
ED  - Buckles, D. J.
TI  - SAS2: a guide to collaborative inquiry and social engagement.
T2  - SAS2: a guide to collaborative inquiry and social engagement
M3  - Book
AB  - This book examines the various processes and techniques and skills involved in Social Analysis Systems (SAS2), a new approach to create and use knowledge for the common good in order to broaden and deepen the range of concepts, tools and transferable skills that can be used to mobilize the power of human intelligence and creativity and to act on the world. The book consists of 26 chapters presented in two parts. Part 1 outlines the concepts that form the basis for the SAS approach to collaborative inquiry and social engagement. The first chapter discusses foundation and skilful means to wisdom and dialogue; the second chapter tackles social analysis and all-purpose techniques; the third, process management; the fourth, guidelines for SAS2events and process design; the fifth, monitoring and evaluation; the sixth, SAS facilitation and active listening; and the seventh, writing guidelines. Part 2 presents a selection of techniques included in training towards professional certification in SAS2. The eighth chapter discusses thinking across boundaries; the ninth, workshop and self-study guidelines; the tenth, assessing the profile of organizations doing joint research on watershed management in Honduras; and the eleventh, insecure village and housing land among the Katkari, Maharashtra, India; the twelfth, the problem of not having a legal title to residential lands in Siddeshwarwadi, Maharashtra, India; the thirteenth, factors influencing the fear of eviction among the Katkari of Sarang Katkarwadi, Maharashtra, India; the fourteenth, a history of events and actions that have harmed or protected Rupa Lake in the Pokhara Valley of Nepal; the fifteenth, reasons for neglect of residential land issues in Navliwadi, Maharashtra, India; the sixteenth, the reason for growing tobacco in Dualatpur, Bangladesh; the seventeenth, validation of a timeline assessment by a milk producers' cooperative in Honduras; the eighteenth, identifying stakeholders in a project to prevent and reduce the impacts of floods and landslides in Nepal; the nineteenth, creating strategic alliances in the tobacco farming areas of Southern Bangladesh; the twentieth, the profile of farming households in tobacco growing regions; the twenty-first, the ideal scenario of legal title in Siddeshwarwadi, Maharashtra, India; the twenty-second, a management plan for the common fishery zone of 262 Ancud, Chile; the twenty-third, competing project priorities of men and women in Mehi, West Bengal; the twenty-fourth, the roles and mutual expectations of workgroups in the CUSO regional office; the twenty-fifth, levels of support for community woodlots in Kajla, West Bengal, India; the twenty-sixth, impacts on knowledge and skills among participants in a youth exchange programme.
