TY  - JOUR
AU  - Nori, M.
TI  - Pastoral livelihoods on the Tibetan Plateau.
T2  - Journal of Agriculture and Environment for International Development
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Poverty, environmental degradation and risk of climatic disasters are major factors challenging pastoral communities throughout the world. Inadequate development policies, ineffective institutional setting and unfair market relationships have often compounded already critical socio-economic conditions and increased the pressure on rich-but-fragile rangelands. These processes undermine pastoral livelihoods and trigger vicious circle to local sustainable development, as pastoralists are critically dependant on the conditions of their resource base. The case of the Tibetan plateau provides with this respect a specific and interesting case. Specific indications and examples are here drawn from ASIA ongoing project in Yushu prefecture, Qinghai province. Pastoralists often represent the most marginalized and vulnerable groups on earth. Their livelihoods are subject to high levels of variability and risk from the environmental, economic and social domains. They have to eke out a living upon variable and unstable environments while facing major difficulties to integrate in the societal frame (Nori & Switzer, 2004). In order to respond to these uncertainties pastoralists have developed a complex form of natural resource management, involving the direct interaction between the three systems in which they operate, i.e. the natural resource system, the resource users system and the larger geo-political system (Pratt et al.1997). The way these three systems interact on the Tibetan plateau and define local pastoral livelihood strategies, vulnerability levels and options for sustainable development in the area will be thoroughly analysed in this article. As it has always been the case for pastoral systems all around the world, relationships between the pastoral society and the central political system have been quite difficult. Development policies for pastoral areas elaborated from the central government have often been 'osmotically inherited' from the policies that had ruled crop-farming agriculture, which traditionally relies on diverse (often opposite) principles. As a result Tibetan herders operate within a normative environment that does not seem to reflect their values, interests and priorities and that is at times contrary to them (ICIMOD, 2000). Institutional efforts addressing poverty alleviation, risk management and environmental issues on the plateau will be here illustrated in order to provide a comprehensive picture of the major factors contributing to define the livelihood of Tibetan pastoral communities.
PU  - Istituto Agronomico per l'Oltremare
