AU  - Banik, Susanta
TI  - Population dynamics and life cycle of pod boring weevil (Apion clavipesGerst) in pigeonpea.
T2  - Journal of Soils and Crops
M3  - Journal article
AB  - The experiment was conducted in the experimental farm and laboratory Department of Entomology, School of Agricultural Sciences, Nagaland University, Medziphema Campus from July, 2022 to January, 2023. Eleven insect pests were reported with pod boring weevil (Apion clavipes) (Coleoptera: Curculionidae) as one of the most destructive insect pests of pigeonpea. The population of A. clavipesstarted to appear during the mid-October i.e.42ndSMW with mean population of 0.60 weevil plant-1. The population gradually started to increase reaching its highest peak during the mid-November i.e.46thSMW with a mean population of 4.40 weevil plant-1and its second peak was observed during the first week of November (45thSMW) with a mean population of 4.20 weevil plant-1. Correlation studies indicated that A. clavipeshad a significant positive correlation to maximum relative humidity but non-significant to maximum and minimum temperature, minimum relative humidity and rainfall. The biological parameters like incubation period, total larval period, total pupal period, pre-oviposition period, oviposition period and development period were recorded about 4.10 0.51, 15.30  1.16, 8.50  0.68, 6.20  0.48, 4.400.32, 27.90 1.71 days, respectively. The adult female with 36.40  2.11 days was found to live longer than the adult male with 28.40 0.66 days. Fecundity was 12.20  0.26 eggs female. The morphometric studies revealed that there was a progressive increase in size between the different developmental stages of Apion clavipes. However, it decreased between the third instar larval stage and pupal stage. Understanding population dynamics and life cycle studies of the pest will help for precise timing of control measures, such as insecticide application or biological control, targeting the most vulnerable stages of the weevil in pigeonpea.
