ED  - Arkhipov, Alexander Geraldovich
TI  - Modern state and prospects of aquaculture development in the Northwestern Caucasus.
T2  - Sustainable fisheries and aquaculture: challenges and prospects for the Blue Bioeconomy
M3  - Book chapter
AB  - The water resources of the Northwestern Caucasus (Krasnodar krai and the Republic of Adygea) suitable for intensive development of aquaculture are considered. Channel, floodplain and estuary ponds, as well as the Azov-Kuban estuaries, the rivers of the Azov-Kuban plain and reservoirs of the Kuban basin are the most promising for fisheries. They are the resource base for the functioning of different categories of industrial fish-farming enterprises (pond, lake-commodity, basin, farm and cage), which annually produce more than 20 thousand tons of marketable fish products. At the same time, the available water bodies are used inefficiently for fishery purposes. Fish productivity in water bodies ranges from 3 to 1600 kg/ha, averaging 178.6 kg/ha. For the purpose of the rational use of the available natural food resources of the water bodies (the Kuban estuaries, rivers of the Azov-Kuban plain and reservoirs of the Kuban basin), their stocking with yearlings of common carp (Cyprinus carpio), silver carp (Hypophthalmichthys molitrix), bighead carp (Hypophthalmichthys nobilis) and grass carp (Ctenopharyngodon idella) with an individual weight no less than 25-30 g is recommended. Black carp (Mylopharyngodon piceus), so-iuy mullet (Liza haematocheilus), paddlefish (Polyodon spathula) etc. can be used as additional species in aquaculture. Activities aimed at restructuring of commercial ichthyocenoses, together with measures of fishery reclamation, will significantly increase the volume of freshwater aquaculture production.
