AU  - Meshreky, Z. S.
TI  - Effect of two different housing systems on the performance of New Zealand white rabbits under hot and mild climatic conditions of middle Egypt.
T2  - Egyptian Poultry Science Journal
M3  - Journal article
AB  - One-hundred-and-forty male and female NZW rabbits aged 6 weeks were used in the study during two periods. In the 1st period (May-October, hot condition), 40 rabbits of each males and females with 798.18.6 g average body weight and another 30 rabbits of both sexes averaging 821.89.8 g body weight were used in the second period (November-April, mild condition). In each period, the animals were divided into two equal groups according to the housing system. The first group was raised in a semi-closed rabbitry and the second was housed in an open rabbitry under a shed. The estimated temperature-humidity index values were 35.34 and 28.41 during the hot climate and 23.45 and 21.02 during the mild climate periods inside the semi-closed building and under the shed, respectively, indicating exposure of rabbits raised in semi-closed building to very severe heat stress and those raised under shed exposed to moderate heat stress during the hot period and absence of heat stress in the mild period. The type of housing (semi-closed system) and period of the year (heat stress) negatively affected many of the studied traits. These effects were significant (P<0.01 or 0.05) on growth performance, dressing percentage, thermoregulatory and haematological responses, some blood plasma constituents for male and female growing rabbits and also testosterone concentration, age at puberty, body weight, weights and histopathological structures of testes and epididymis, reaction time and semen characteristics of male rabbits. Mortality rate increased (P<0.05) with increasing air temperature during hot period for rabbits housed in the semi-closed system, and with decreasing air temperature during mild period for rabbits raised in open system. Exposure of young doe rabbits reared in semi-closed system to very severe heat stress adversely affected (P<0.01 or 0.05) body weight, oestrogen concentration, ovary weights, number of Graffian follicles and reproductive efficiency during the first parity. Results obtained in the present study indicate that the open housing system is the most favorable housing during hot period in middle Egypt, which reduces the deleterious effects resulting in stressful hot conditions and improves economical efficiency in rabbit meat production or breeding.
