TI  - Seventh pasture milk test of dairy zebu at Embrapa Cerrados: results booklet for the dairy Gir breed.
T2  - Documentos - Embrapa Cerrados
M3  - Bulletin
AB  - The seventh zootechnical test for milk production on pasture, carried out by Embrapa Cerrados and the Zebu Breeders Association of Planalto (ACZP) in Brazil, aimed to select the best Gir dairy heifers in this cycle by measuring important economic parameters for milk production under pasture conditions in the cerrado biome. This is the only Brazilian test to evaluate the complete lactation of zebu heifers on pasture. This zootechnical test took place under the climatic conditions of the cerrado in the Federal District. The animals did not receive hormonal stimulation for milk production or ejection. Milk production parameters, milk composition (fat, protein and somatic cell count), lactation persistence and reproduction were evaluated during 305 days of lactation of the females. Morphological evaluation, genotyping for beta-casein A2A2 and genomic evaluations of the heifers were also performed. This evaluation provides a better estimate of the genetic potential of each animal. This information supports the decision making of the breeder based on more reliable technical information. This work contributes to the fulfillment of Sustainable Development Goal (SDG) number 2. The use of zebu cattle adapted to tropical conditions is essential for the sustainability of pasture-based milk production systems. Due to their resilience and the production of quality, low-cost milk, efforts to genetically improve dairy zebu cattle contribute to adaptation to climate change, extreme weather conditions, droughts and other disasters. The 17 SDGs were established by the United Nations (UN) in 2015 and comprise a global agenda for the construction and implementation of public policies that aim to guide humanity until 2030.
