AU  - Komiyama, H.
AU  - Chantsaldulam, R.
AU  - Du FuLin, Du FuLin
TI  - The present situation and the future direction of animal husbandry in Mongolia.
T2  - JIRCAS Working Report
M3  - Bulletin article
AB  - In Mongolia, with the transition from a planned economy to a market economy beginning in the early 1990s, the animal husbandry management mode has changed from collective operation by the agricultural cooperatives (Negdel) to individual operation by each household. The number of herders and livestock has increased very rapidly. Thus, overgrazing has become a significant problem. Weather conditions have also contributed to fluctuations in livestock farming. During the cold-snow disasters (Dzud) of 1999-2002, the number of livestock was reduced by 30%. Livestock numbers then increased rapidly again, reaching a record high in 2009. However, 10.32 million livestock died from the cold-snow disaster in the winter and spring of 2010. This paper analyzes current practices of Mongolian animal husbandry for the purpose of making viable suggestions for its future development. Several important indicators are studied. Mongolian animal husbandry is submitted to international comparison, focusing on Inner Mongolia and New Zealand, which is second only to Mongolia in total number of livestock per capita. Mongolian import/export rates of animal products are studied in relation to various factors, including the rapidly growing consumer demand for dairy products in urban centers, required amounts of livestock feed, and nomadic herding, which poses unique problems associated with transportation difficulties and food quality. Using a representative north-central region of Mongolia for example purposes, this paper concludes that intensive animal husbandry is vital to the future direction of livestock farming in Mongolia.
PU  - Japan International Research Center for Agricultural Sciences
PA  - Tsukuba
DA  - 2013
PY  - 2013
IS  - No.78
