TI  - Using innovative approaches in selecting and disseminating bean varieties in Mozambique: lessons learnt.
T2  - 10th African Crop Science Conference Proceedings, Maputo, Mozambique, 10-13 October 2011
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - The common bean (Phaseolus vulgarisL.) is widely grown by many farmers for food and cash income in various agroecologies in Mozambique. Most farmers use local bean varieties, either because they do not like the improved bean varieties or they are unaware of the new bean varieties; or they have no access to seed of new bean varieties. The lack of preference for improved bean varieties is often associated with the fact that in the past, breeders selected varieties at the research stations and made recommendations to farmers in a top-down approach, which resulted in low and slow adoption of the varieties by farmers. As a result, farmers continue to use their traditional varieties, which are low yielding. This study was initiated to increase stakeholders' participation in the variety selection processes, followed by instituting innovative ways of making bean seed available to farmers through various dissemination channels. As many as 20 released and promising bean varieties were exposed to farmers across 30 sites in Nampula, Tete and Zambezia provinces. Participatory variety selection (PVS) processes were used, where participating farmers, traders and extension agents were disaggregated by gender (418 female and 603 male), to capture different bean variety selection criteria by gender. The results showed that the major selection criteria used were: high yielding; high marketability which was mostly based on seed size and colour, resistance to pests and diseases, tolerance to drought and erect growth habit. It was interesting to note that while males were more interested in marketable varieties, females wanted varieties which were high yielding as well as marketable. The most preferred varieties across the sites were VTTT923/10-3, VTTT925/9-1-2, SUG131, CAL143 and AFR703. After the selection, 141 farmers were involved in startup seed production and they were able to make these varieties accessible to about 3,000 other farmers.
