TI  - An ILPH programme to improve the quality of forage available for equids in rural Mexico.
T2  - Fifth International Colloquium on Working Equines. The future for working equines. Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, 30 October-2 November, 2006.
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - Equids are an important source of power in many rural areas of Mexico. On the hillside Campesino (smallholder) farms in Central Mexico, seasonal fluctuations in grass growth mean that there are times when grazing for equids does not meet requirements. To help in feeding animals over these period campesinos grow oats and/or maize as a forage crop and save crop residues. This paper describes a project to help Campesino farmers improve the quality of their forage crop by seeding spring vetch with the forage crop to increase the protein content and digestibility of the crop and at the same time benefit soil fertility through the nitrogen fixing properties of the vetch. Farmers from three areas in Mexico (Altzayanca in the State of Tlaxcala and San Bartolo and Chiquispac in the State of Mexico) joined the project. The project is a partnership between ILPH, who provide vetch seed, and the farmers who provide all other inputs necessary to produce the forage crop. Farmer practices were recorded in the second and third year of the project and in the second year agronomic and nutritional characteristics were recorded on fifteen plots in five villages where the vetch was grown with oats. Total fodder biomass production SD averaged 6.51.99 tonne DM/ha. The mean ratio vetch:oats:weeds was 0.19:0.61:0.18. The leaf:stem ratio in the oat fraction was 0.30:0.70. Average contents of organic matter (OM, 92410 g), crude protein (CP, 10120 g), cellular contents (38568 g), neutral detergent fibre (NDF, 61568 g) and acid detergent fibre (ADF, 37736 g) per kg of dry matter were better (higher crude protein and lower fibre contents) than the average values for the forages traditionally used. The results are discussed in relation to farming practices. Problems in growing the forage mixture included erratic rainfall in these mountainous areas, local summer hail storms and early autumn frosts, all of which made saving seed from the crop difficult. Although not quantified, most farmers said that the addition of vetch to the forage crop improved body condition when it was fed to their equids, compared to feeding traditional forages.
