AU  - Ajit Menon, Ajit Menon
AU  - Subramanian Karuppiah, Subramanian Karuppiah
AU  - Stephen, J.
TI  - Reconfiguring the coast.
T2  - Economic and Political Weekly
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This article examines the factors behind the reconfiguration of the Koodal Kayal coastal fishing village of the Tirunelveli district in Tamil Nadu, India, which the villagers perceive to have only further marginalized them despite the substantial post-tsunami relief and rehabilitation that would have provided the opportunity for genuine development. Since its inception in 1991, the coastal regulation zone has been amended 19 times but it is argued that this regulation only cleared the way for much more development activity such as the nuclear power plant along the Koodal Kayal coast that could either result in the displacement of fishing villages and fishers or to increased pollution. The M S Swaminathan Committee Report of 2004 highlighted this contradiction by recommending that instead of coastal regulation zones, coastal management zones be adopted and that areas are classified according to vulnerability criteria. But while all the right noises have been made about preserving ecological diversity, cultural heritage and the rights of fishing communities, little has been said as to how this will be done. In the aftermath of the December 2004 tsunami, RS 17 crore has been spent in Koodal Kayal alone, for relief and rehabilitation. Great efforts were made by the Tamil Nadu government to make sure that relief and rehabilitation were well-coordinated. Yet developments suggest at times, a lack of coordination between different institutions and lack of transparency with regards to the process of local consultation. Villagers also argue that a planned highway is meant to facilitate movement to the nuclear power plant and not to help villagers. Moreover, while it cannot be disputed that NGOs played an important role in the relief effort, it is argued that their advocacy role in the rehabilitation process and their support of fishers' rights are much less prominent than expected. Thus, it is argued that the tsunami just provided an opportunity for investment into the development of the coast as a zone, to be increased manifold, and for the state to promote its developmental agenda further. Integrated coastal zone management should not only be about sustainable development, but also about what type of sustainable development and for whom. But it is argued that coastal management in villages such as Koodal Kayal has forsaken the "for whom" question. In conclusion, the further marginalization of the Koodal Kayal village can be attributed to disaster capitalism and the state's vision of coastal development long before the tsunami.
