TI  - Effects of rice straw mulching on soil temperature and moisture regulation in red upland soil.
T2  - RDA Journal of Agro-Environment Science
M3  - Journal article
AB  - A field trial with a summer maize variety Liyu 23 was conducted in 2006 in red upland soil in Wulingshan mountain area, Hunan, China, to investigate effects of rice straw mulching (RSM) on soil temperature and soil moisture under rainfed conditions, in which 4 treatments designed include control treatment without rice straw, and 3 RSM treatments at 5000, 10000 and 15000 kg/ha. The RSM could significantly reduce soil temperature in top 0-5 cm soil layer at 15:00 by 1.6-4.1°C averagely, and the effects of temperature reduction was enlarged with the amount of rice straw mulching. The RSM could also significantly enhance water holding capacity in top 0-5 cm soil layer. In the high air temperature and drought period, the lowest content of soil moisture in the top 0-5 cm soil layer increased by 3.3-3.6% at 5000-10000 kg RSM/ha and 6.1% at 15000 RSM/ha. In the RSM treatments, leaf photosynthetic rate increased by 8.34-17.77molm-2s-1at jointing stage and 4.46-11.27molm-2s-1at female flower initiation, and the kernel yield was enhanced by 7.6-13.1%. Considering the acceptable effects on reducing soil temperature and maintaining soil moisture, the proper amount of RSM selected should be 5000 kg/ha in the red upland soil in the hilly area of Hunan province.
