TI  - Promotion ofMoringaproducts via an inclusive value chain for economic, social and environmental impacts in Africa.
T2  - Acta Horticulturae
M3  - Journal article
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - One of the biggest challenges facing West African countries is how to create opportunities for the millions of women and young people to live meaningful lives and sustained livelihoods. Mali is a landlocked country where 80% of the population practice agriculture as their main source of income. The country is endowed with abundant fertile lands yet farming communities continue to be affected by food insecurity and malnutrition. Climate change affects considerably the agriculture sector with problems related to erosion, drought and irregular rainfall. Each year, 6 million t of wood are exploited by the population for fuelwood. Fuelwood constitutes more than 90% of total national energy use in the country. Deforestation and soil erosion remain one of the two main environmental problems. For Mali to meet the 2030 Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) agenda and improve the living standards of the population, it is important to find new directions in scaling up production, processing local raw materials and exporting worldwide. This paper proposes a green innovative method to create economic, social and environmental impacts via the promotion and commercialization ofMoringaproducts with an inclusive value chain including the most vulnerable people, women and youth. Classified as a "Superfood",Moringa oleiferais a fast growing, drought, harsh climate, sun- and heat-loving tree that can grow up to 2 m particularly suitable for dryland countries such as Mali. By developing an effective buyer-driven approach with women and young farmers in rural areas, promotingMoringaplanting in all over the country and by commercializing processedMoringaleaves into tea, powder and oil, will contribute to creating economic, social and environmental impacts in Africa region and ensure sustainability by making profits out of the commercialization.
