TI  - Development of the milk chain in the periurban area of Niamey (Niger).
T2  - Journal of Agriculture and Environment for International Development
M3  - Journal article
AB  - In the last years the process of urbanization and the population growth caused a change in food needs of big cities in the Sahel area. The increasing demand of milk and derivates is fulfilled by the import of big quantities of dried milk from the surplus countries. Local milk production should be improved to permit these countries to unburden themselves of their economical ties and to reduce the health problems related to the use of dried milk. The aim of this study was to obtain the livestock, social and economic information of two periurban villages in Niamey (Niger). The study was based on a questionnaire concerning breeder's personal information, the herd live, herd distribution, livestock management and veterinary practices, animals health and the valorization of milk production. The questionnaire, translated from French intoFulfunde(Fulani native language), was organized in questions without multiple choices and it has been carried out from 15 April to 30 May 2003. The census involved 81 breeders: they belong to the Fulani ethnic group, they are not member of any organization or NGO and they have been living in the peri-urban area of Niamey for at least ten years, leaving rural areas because of drought and the economical crisis. The zebu cattle breeds (Bos indicus) were: Azaouak, Djeli, Goudali and Bororo. The natural pasture is the basic diet of the herd and the food supplement is based on the straw associated to the cereal bran (mainly millet and corn). The milking is carried out only by men, twice a day before going and coming back from the pasture. The transformation in curdled milk and butter is a women duty and women sometimes go to the city to sell such products. On the contrary, raw milk is sold by men only. This study has identified many constrains to the development of milk production; solving these problems will permit to improve milk production in urban and periurban Niamey area.
